<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-541-878  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 541 878.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>InfoWorld  June 4 1990 v12 n23 p70(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Windows 3.0 steers us toward a decade ruled by graphics. (TechStreet) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Gantz, John.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The computer graphics industry has barely worked its way out ofniche status.andP;  It garnered $26.3 billion in 1989, but that is asmall percentage of the whole computer market.andP;  Half of the marketcould be attributed to the sale of proprietary systems.andP;  The 1990swill be the decade of graphics and internetworking.andP;  By 1993, lessthan 30 percent of computer graphics revenue will come fromproprietary systems, and a large part of the market will begeneral-purpose platforms running dedicated graphics applicationsand platforms running applications with embedded graphicscomponents.andP;  This means that the 1990s will also be the decadewhen the computer industry gets out of the character mode and intothe pixel mode.andP;  Some ramifications of this switch are discussed.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Product:   Microsoft Windows 3.0 (Graphical user interface) (usage).andO;Topic:     Computer GraphicsIndustry AnalysisFuture of ComputingForecasting.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>